'Iron(II) oxide', also known by its former name 'ferrous oxide' or informally as
'iron monoxide', is one of the iron oxides. It is a black-colored powder with
the chemical formula . It consists of the chemical element iron in the oxidation
state of 2 bonded to oxygen. Its mineral form is known as wÃ¼stite. Iron(II)
oxide should not be confused with rust, which usually consists of hydrated
iron(III) oxide (ferric oxide). The term may be used more loosely for a non-
stoichiometric compound as the ratio of the elements iron and oxygen can vary;
samples are typically iron deficient with compositions ranging from
Fe 0.84 O to Fe 0.95 O.
